Introduction¶

YouTube is a social media platform that allows users to watch creators' videos. These videos can be about any topic, such as sports, entertainment, education, and music. As YouTube became more and more popular, creators started earning money based on how well their videos did. In fact, in today's society, some YouTubers (content creators) have made videos for their audience to enjoy their full-time jobs and become millionaires by doing so. Currently, YouTubers get paid on how many views they get per video; the more views a video has, the more money they get for that video. Here is a reference for how YouTubers earn money and how much they earn based off of videos: https://www.creditkarma.com/income/i/how-much-do-youtubers-make.

There are some problems with this, though. People could buy bots, or fake views, which could increase their view count artificially. A better way to track how well a video is doing is based on comments. If a video has a lot of comments, that means that a lot of real people viewed the video and wanted to discuss or interact with the creator. So, the more comments a YouTuber gets on their videos, the bigger community that YouTuber has. A bigger community can help YouTubers get money in other ways too. Content creators can get money through sponsorships or merchandise, and the more non-artificial people they have interacting with their video, the more likely they will get a sponsorship. Also, that means that it is probable that they will sell more merch, as artificial people cannot buy merch. Therefore, the amount of comments should be looked at for how well a YouTuber is doing and how much they should get paid.

This project uses a dataset that shows tens of thousands of YouTube videos and information about those videos, such as their likes, dislikes, comment count, the date and time that they were uploaded, and the description of the videos. This dataset contains the most popular YouTube videos, found from YouTube's most trending videos list. These parameters are used to analyze overall trends in the data to show how the amount of comments correlates with the other aspects relating to human interaction with the videos. We will use and explain the data science lifecycle to portray this analysis. This tutorial will show you how to collect the data, process the data, analyze and visualize the data, make inferences and predictions, including using machine learning, based on the data, and what all of that means.

Step 3: This step consists of data cleaning. In general, data cleaning is the removal and correction of invalid data. This is important to do so that the analysis is as accurate as possible. The code below removes all of the data that contains non-ascii text in the "descriptions" (video descriptions) column. Anything that is not considered normal text must be removed because some of our analysis performed later will be more accurate if those non-ascii characters are removed.

In order to actually filter out the invalid data, the first step we need to do is to create a boolean mask. A boolean mask is an array-like data structure that stores booleans for whether or not each observation/row in the dataframe meets a certain requirement. In this case, for each row we check if the column for the video description contains only ascii characters. We then negate our boolean mask in order to drop (delete) all invalid observations from our dataframe.

Note the deleted indices in the snippet of the dataframe below compared to our initial dataframe.

In [99]:
# Remove each observation whose description contains non-ASCII text

bool_mask = df['description'].apply(lambda x: str(x).isascii())
non_ascii_mask = ~bool_mask

df = df.drop(df[non_ascii_mask].index, axis=0)

Step 4: This step involves more data cleaning. Now, we are fixing the dates and times and then converting them from strings to a datetime object. Datetime is an object that makes it easier to manipuate and analyze the date and times, which will be useful later on. To convert the strings to datetime, the string must be in a certain format. To convert both the year and the time, the format must be "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S". For this dataset, we noticed there was a '000Z' at the end of all the terms. After doing some research, we realized this corresponds to the timezone. To verify that all objects were in the same time zone we used a boolean mask and saw every video in our dataframe had the exact same term so we can just remove it. To remove it, we just used the apply function and went through every row. In each row, we went to the "publish_time" column, or the column that is currently storing the date and time as a string, and replaced the ".000Z" with an empty string. Now that the timezone is removed, we are ready to convert to datetime. We took the whole "publish_time" column and added a new column to the dataframe that used pandas' "to_datetime" function to convert the strings from the "publish_time" column into a datetime object. After we went through the whole "publish_time" column, that data was useless to us since we had the exact same data as datetime objects, so we dropped that column.

Step 6: This step involves a combination of data cleaning and data extraction. When looking at the snippet of the dataframe above, we can see that the category_id column simply stores an integer; this is not that useful to us since it is a categorical variable without a category name. However, we have the data to fill in this information as part of the dataset we downloaded. There is a JSON file, view more info on JSON files here: https://blog.hubspot.com/website/json-files, called US_category_id.json that contains all of the info required to replace the integers for category id with the actual category names.

To do this, we first need to load in the JSON file which we can simply do using json.load(file), which loads the json file as a python dictionary. We then use python list comprehension in order to extract the neccesary category information as a list of tuples of category id number to category name. We then define a function to make this replacement for a given row in our dataframe and use the pandas dataframe.apply method to make make this swap for every row.

In [102]:
with open('Data/US_category_id.json', 'r') as file:
    data = json.load(file)
categories_list = [(item["id"], item["snippet"]["title"]) for item in data["items"]]

def str_cat_id(x):

    for y in categories_list:

        if str(x) == str(y[0]):

            return y[1]

    return np.nan


df['category_id'] = df['category_id'].apply(lambda x: str_cat_id(x))
df.head()

Exploratory Analysis and Data Visualization¶

Step 7: Now that we have cleaned all the data that we are planning on using, we can start analyzing and visualizing that data. In this step, we are comparing the years to views for each category ID (explained above). We group each category_id using the pandas "groupby" function, explained here: https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.groupby.html. Then, we go through each group and plot each year (from our datetime column) as the x-axis and the change in views for that category over those years. The "plt.subplots" creates a subplot, meaning it creates the actual plot where the points will be graphed onto. The grp.plot() line is the one that actually plots the data onto the graph. "Grp" is each group and the parameters for the plot() are the plot, the type of plot, which is a line plot in this case, then the x axis, which is the date, the y axis, which is the views, and the label, which will be used for the legend. "Plt.title" is used to give a title to the plot. "Plt.xlabel" is the title of the x-axis of the plot. "Plt.ylabel" is the title of the y-label of the plot. "Plt.legend" displays the legend, which, in this case, shows the color for each category. "Plt.grid" shows a grid in the background.

A guide for the most common matplotlib functions are explained here: https://matplotlib.org/stable/gallery/subplots_axes_and_figures/subplots_demo.html

Hypotheses Testing¶

Step 10: Since the main result that we want to examine is the comment count for each video, we want to find out what the relation is between views and comment. To do this, lets create a simple linear regression.

The first step in this process is to extract the variables from our dataframe that we want to examine which we do via column selection from our dataframe. In this case we select views (independent variable) and comment_count (dependent variable). We then want to set up a least squares problem, where (in general) we want to find m and b such that y^(x) = mx+b is the best possible predictor of y(x). Least squares defines this optimal predictor as the predictor function that minimizes the sum of squares of the residuals. A residual is the difference between the value that our model predicts for a given x and actual value. We can set this up as a linear system and try to find such that X = Y^ minimizes distance between Y^ and Y We can calculate by solving = (X^T X)^-1 X^T * Y. To do this in Python, we can convert our extracted columns into two numpy arrays, one for our independent variables and one for our dependent variables. Since we want to fit our data to y^ = mx + b, we need to also account for our intercept term. We can do this by creating a column in our X numpy array that is all ones. We then use numpy's least squares function with X and Y to find our slope and intercept for our regression line.

To plot the regression line, we simply use plt's plot() function, inputting our x variables, and use our intercept and slope to calculate our predicted values. We can use plt's scatter function to plot the actual values.

In [577]:
df_lin_reg = df[['views', 'comment_count']]
np_lin_reg = df_lin_reg.values
X = np_lin_reg[:,0]
X_ones = np.vstack([X, np.ones(len(X))]).T
Y = np_lin_reg[:,1]

lst_sq, residual, _, _ = np.linalg.lstsq(X_ones, Y, rcond=None)
slope, intercept = lst_sq

fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=1)
ax.scatter(df['views'], df['comment_count'])
ax.plot(X, intercept + slope*X, 'r')
ax.set_title('Comments as a function of Views')
ax.set_xlabel('Views')
ax.set_ylabel('Comments')
plt.show()

Explanation of Graph This graph shows comments as a function of views, and the corresponding linear regression. Visually, there appears to be a positive linear correlation, however it does not appear to be a strong correlation.

Step 11: Lets verify our claims from above: we will perform hypothesis testing. To get statistics about our regression, we can use statsmodels's ordinary least squares function, where we define that we want comment_count as a function of views. We can then print a summary table which includes all of the data necessary for model analysis. From the table, the two most important pieces of information are the R-squared value and the F-Statistic. R-squared tells us the proportion of the variance in our dependent variable that is explained by our regression model (Analysis in next section). The F-statistic tests whether at least one of the regression coefficients is significantly different from zero, indicating whether the overall regression model provides a better fit to the data than a model with no predictors.

In addition, we need to calculate our critical value which we will compare to our F statistic. To do this, we need a siginificnce level (alpha = 0.05), and need to know the number of degrees of freedom and the degree of freedom residuals which can be seen from the OLS summary.

You can read more on stats model formulas here: https://www.statsmodels.org/dev/examples/notebooks/generated/formulas.html

In [578]:
lin_reg = smf.ols(formula="comment_count ~ views ", data=df).fit()
print(lin_reg.summary())

alpha = 0.05
dfn = 1 #k (degrees of freedom)
dfd = 16983 #n - k -1

critical_val = f.ppf(1-alpha, dfn, dfd)
print("critical_val: ", critical_val)

Analysis of Regression: If we have our null hypothesis H0 be there is no relationship between views and comments, then we would reject that hypothesis. The reason we reject this hypothesis is that since alpha = 0.05, based on our dataset we have a critical value of 3.842. From the OLS linear regression data, we have an F statistic of 7274. Since our critical value is less than our F statistic, we reject our null hypothesis. Thus there is a relationship between views and comments.

Since we have an R-squared value of 0.3, that means that 30% of the variance in our comment count is explained by our regression model.

Step 12: Even though our model was statistically significant, the accuracy of it was relatively low as seen by the R-squared value. What if we examine each video category seperately? To do this, we once again use the pandas groupby function to seperate based on category. We then iterate over each video category and create a regression line using scipy.stats.linregress for each category seperately.

We use smf.ols to account for an interaction and we do this by specifying categories*other_var as the independent variable in our stats model formula. Afterwards, the steps for analysis are the same as before.

Step 14: It seems like our second linear regression is better than our first; but can we prove this statistically? To do this we need to conduct a comparison f test, read more here: https://sites.duke.edu/bossbackup/files/2013/02/FTestTutorial.pdf, which looks to see if a model fits our dataset than another model. Luckily for us, statsmodels linear regression has a built in function to compute the F statistic; so we just need to compute our new critical value which is once again similar to before.

In [470]:
f_val, p_val, diff_df = lin_reg2.compare_f_test(lin_reg) # returns f val, p val, difference in df
print("F-Statistic: ", f_val)

alpha = 0.05
dfn = lin_reg2.df_model - lin_reg.df_model
dfd = lin_reg2.df_resid
critical_val = f.ppf(1-alpha, dfn, dfd)

print("critical_val: ", critical_val)

F-Statistic:  196.98314642313827
critical_val:  1.459777783506337

Analysis of Regression: Our null hypothesis is that our original linear regression is just as good as our model which accounts for the category type. From our F test, we get an F statistic of 196.98 and since we have a significance level of 0.05, our critical value is 1.4598 so our F statistic is greater than our critical value which means we reject the null hypothesis. Thus, our model which accounts for the video category and views is statistically better than our model which only accounts for views.

Step 15: Based on our initial dataset, what other information can we extract? One place that we can look is at the video description column which gives a good synopsis about what the video is about. We can apply sentiment analysis on each video description to find out the sentiment of each video. To do this, we use the VADER sentiment analysis tool, read more here: https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/2021/06/vader-for-sentiment-analysis/. We first create a sentiment analyzer object and use the pandas apply function to calculate the sentiment for the description for each video in our dataset. We then extract the compound score to get a singular value describing the sentiment, how positive or negative a piece of text is, and store it as a new column in our data frame.

We can also compute a new variable to describe the relation between likes and dislikes. Ideally, this would tell us how much people like a video. One issue with simply taking a simple ratio between likes and dislikes is that videos with a higher dislike rate will have a ratio that approaches 0 while videos with a higher like rate approach infinity. To combat this, we take the log of this ratio.

In [471]:
sia = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

df['sentiment'] = df['description'].apply(lambda x: sia.polarity_scores(str(x))['compound'])
df['like_dislike_ratio'] = df.apply(lambda x: np.log(x['likes']/x['dislikes']) if x['dislikes'] != 0 else np.NaN, axis=1)

What about the upload date of the video?

Explanation of code: This code is pretty much the same as the previous one in that it plots the datetime against the comment count and creates a residual line based on the data. The only difference, though, is that we are dealing with datetime. Since we want to perform least squares, we need the values of the datetime to be a number. We do this by creating a new column, "upload_datetime_numeric." For each value in the upload_datetime column, a timestamp object with the date 01/01/1970 is created and subtracted from that datetime value. The point of this is to subtract the Unix epoch, which is the standard UTC time. This creates a timedelta object with the value being the amount of time away from 01/01/1970. Then, we perform integer division with 1s to convert the timedelta value into seconds so that it can be more easily used in the least squares computation.

Machine Learning¶

Step 18: This part of the code focuses on machine learning. It uses gradient descent with ridge regression to predict the comment count based on views. Gradient descent is an algorithm that minimizes loss by iteratively adjusting its parameters. It computes the gradient based off of the initial parameters and then updates the parameters in the opposite direction of the gradient to minimze loss. Then, it repeats this process with the new parameters. It does this for a specified number of times, called epochs. In this case, the gradient descent algorithm also uses ridge regression. Ridge regression is a technique used to improve the stability of the linear regression model by preventing overfitting. Overfitting occurs when a model trains the data too well, leading to noise and other details that are not important being captured.

This code first creates a copy of the second dataframe. The second dataframe is a list of all rows where the column "column_id" is "Education" since that is the category we want to focus on. So, out of the 412 rows that have education as their category, we are choosing to remove 80 of them. In Machine Learning, you do not take the whole dateset to train. Instead, you take around 80% of the dataset to train and keep the rest to the side. So, we randomly choose 80 indices to remove from the list and keep the rest as a part of our training model.

Now that we have our training model, we can start the machine learning process. We choose our views column as the independent variable and our comment_count column as the dependent variable. On the independent variable, we make it homogenous by adding a column of ones to the end. This column will be used for analyzing the bias. Then, we perform gradient descent with ridge regression on the x and y variables. We run the gradient descent with ridge regression algorithm for a specific number of epochs. In this case, that number is 10000000. We do this with a learning rate of 0.00000000000000001 and lambda being 0.000000000001. The learning rate determines how quickly or slowly an algorithm adjusts the parameters during the training process. Lambda is the regularization parameter. It helps prevent overfitting by penalizing large coefficients in the regression model.

There is a lot of trial and error that goes into finding the proper paremeters for the gradient descent. We had to play around with the epochs, learning rate, and lambda to ensure that our loss is continually decreasing as the number of epochs increases.

The result of the gradient descent with ridge regression on this specific data with views as the independent variable and comment_count as the dependent variable is a linear regression model that contains the theta and loss. Theta is the weights, or parameters, of the linear regression model with ridge regression. Each value in theta corresponds to the independent variables. In this case, there is only one independent variable, but there is also the bias to look at. So, the first value in theta is for the views and the second value is for the bias, which is the intercept of the linear regression model. It indicates the expected value of the target variable (comment_count in this case) when all the features (in this case, views) are zero. The loss shows us how far away we are from the actual target values. The bigger the loss, the further away we are. The whole point of seeing the loss is that as the model runs through more and more iterations, it should learn from the last iteration and the loss should decrease. In this case, the loss does do that, as shown by the fact that the first loss is 1.58974459e+09 and the final loss is 1.88238589e+08.

df3 = df2.copy()
df3.reset_index(inplace=True)
df3.drop('index', axis=1, inplace=True)

idx = np.random.choice(df3.shape[0], 80, replace=False)

index_array = df3.index.to_numpy()

for i in idx:
	
	mask = index_array != i
	index_array = index_array[mask]

train = df3.loc[index_array]

x = np.array(train[['views']])
y = np.array(train['comment_count'])

ones_column = np.ones((x.shape[0], 1))
x = np.concatenate((x, ones_column), axis=1)

# gradient descent with ridge regression
def grad_descent(X,y,T,alpha, lambda_reg):
    m, n = X.shape
    theta = np.zeros(n)
    f = np.zeros(T)
    for i in range(T):
        f[i] = 0.5 * np.linalg.norm(X.dot(theta) - y)**2 + 0.5 * lambda_reg * np.linalg.norm(theta)**2
        g = np.transpose(X).dot(X.dot(theta) - y)
        theta = theta* (1 - (alpha*lambda_reg)/m) - alpha * g
    return(theta,f)

T = 10000000
alpha = 0.00000000000000001
lambda_reg = 0.000000000001

theta, loss = grad_descent(x, y, T, alpha, lambda_reg)

print("Views Theta: ", theta[0])
print("Bias: ", theta[1])
print("All losses: \n", loss/(x.shape[1]))
print("Final Loss: ", loss[-1]/x.shape[1])

Before we can create a neural network, we must first prepare our data. We then define our neural network. In this case we define a very simple neural network which only has two linear layers, layers that perform linear transformations on the data. However, we must have an activation function in between these layers in order to have truly seperate network layers. In this case we use ReLU: read more here https://builtin.com/machine-learning/relu-activation-function. It is important to note that the output size of one network layer must be equal to the input size of the next layer.

In [515]:
class SimpleNN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(SimpleNN, self).__init__()
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(3, 20)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(20, 1)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = F.relu(self.fc1(x))
        x = self.fc2(x)
        return x

We then define our training loop which is where our model does the actual learning. Before that though, we must define our loss function which measures the difference between the predicted output and the actual target values. We use this loss in order to accurately train our model. We chose to use Mean Squared Error Loss which is a common loss function for regression; read more here: https://www.simplilearn.com/tutorials/statistics-tutorial/mean-squared-error#:~:text=The%20Mean%20Squared%20Error%20measures,it%20relates%20to%20a%20function. We also must define our optimizer, which is what updates the weights for our model. We choose to use Adam which you can read more about here: https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/adam-optimizer/.

To actually train our model, we must use our data loader which we defined in the previous block to load the current batch of data to be processed. We then make a prediction, evaluate our predictions, and use our optimizer function to update our weights.

In [567]:
model = SimpleNN()
criterion = nn.MSELoss()
optimizer = optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=0.000001)
num_epochs = 25001

total_loss = []

for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    for inputs, labels in train_loader:
        
        # Forward pass
        outputs = model(inputs) # make predictions
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels) # evaluate predictions
        
        # Backward pass and optimization
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()

    total_loss.append(loss.item())
    
    if(epoch%500 == 0):
        print(f'Epoch [{epoch+1}/{num_epochs}], Loss: {loss.item():.4f}')

test = df3.iloc[idx]
x = np.array(test[['views', 'likes', 'upload_datetime_numeric']])
y = np.array(test['comment_count']).reshape(-1,1)

x = torch.tensor(x, dtype=torch.float32)
y = torch.tensor(y, dtype=torch.float32)

dataset = TensorDataset(x, y)
test_loader = DataLoader(dataset, batch_size=2, shuffle=True)

model.eval()
with torch.no_grad():
    predictions = model(x)
    mse = criterion(predictions, y).item()
    print(f'Mean Squared Error on test set: {mse:.4f}')

    # Calculate R-squared
    ss_total = torch.sum((y - torch.mean(y)) ** 2).item()  # Total sum of squares
    ss_residual = torch.sum((y - predictions) ** 2).item() # Residual sum of squares
    r2_score = 1 - (ss_residual / ss_total)
    print(f'R-squared on test set: {r2_score:.4f}')

Interpretation¶

Through our analysis of the YouTube Trending Dataset, we have concluded that the most important variables to predict the comment count for a video are views, likes and upload date. From this, we can create a very accurate model to predict video comments. From this, YouTube content creators can understand what are the important things to focus on improving in order to help generate revenue. We have also realized that it is important for content creators to focus on their specific category, since it appears to be a different model across categories to predict comments.

Now that we have interpreted our results, we have completed a walkthrough of the entire data science lifecycle.
